        "recipientId" : "52522040",
        "text" : "And here‚Äôs the illusionism abstract\n\nIllusionism, Then and Now \nBryce Huebner, Georgetown University\nEyal Aviv, George Washington University\nSonam Kachru, University of Virginia\n\nAbstract: Contemporary illusionists, as well as pre-modern YogƒÅcƒÅra philosophers, appeal to magical illusions as a way of clarifying their claims about the constructive nature of typical human cognition. But the import of this appeal to magic diverges in intriguing ways across these traditions. On the one hand, contemporary illusionists argue that qualitative or phenomenal experiences are like magical illusions, which are produced when introspective mechanisms bundle together the outputs of numerous neuro-computational systems, and present them as simple and unified phenomena; this claim does not extend beyond the domain of phenomenal consciousness; and, the account of this illusion is always specified in terms of computational processes. On the other hand, pre-modern YogƒÅcƒÅra philosophers argue that all of the apparently stable and persisting contents of experience are illusory; they do not directly target phenomenal consciousness; and, their account of how such illusions are produced and sustained appeals to the stances we adopt in attempting to make the world that we encounter intelligible, rather than assuming that a specific kind of causal relation can be treated as ultimately real. Our aim in this paper is to explore the implications of adopting a YogƒÅcƒÅra approach to illusionism, as an alternative way of treating mental phenomena as natural phenomena, which are amenable to re-description. Unlike contemporary illusionists, who hold that successful re-description always depends on improved prediction and explanation, we argue that YogƒÅcƒÅra philosophers pursue an approach according to which successful re-description is also normatively constrained by soteriological considerations. And we argue that this form of illusionism discloses the possibility of transformative practices, which have the potential to restructure our experience of the world in normatively significant ways.",
        "mediaUrls" : [ ],
