        "recipientId" : "52522040",
        "text" : "Crap! I wrote it on my phone...will try to upload from my computer in a bit. But this was the long question:\n\nAnalytic philosophers often seem to think that there is an answer to questions like ‚Äúwhat is it like to be an X‚Äù. My strong suspicion is that there is nothing in the world that is stable enough to serve as an answer to that kind of question. They also seem to suppose that there should be answers to question like ‚Äúwhat is it like to smell a rotten egg‚Äù. My strong suspicion is that there are no viable answers to these kinds of questions either (I would defer to A.S. Barwich on olfaction, but as I read her work smells are pretty clearly illusory in the relevant sense; and I think that similar cases can be developed pretty easily everywhere outside the domain of vision‚Äîthe difficulties in making a case for vision are interesting, but I don‚Äôt want to dwell on them here). So far, I‚Äôm willing to follow you down a roughly elliminativist trajectory.  But I don‚Äôt think we should try to eliminate all the way through, as you sometimes seem to want to do. \n\nConsider a common Buddhist example: the rope mistakenly perceived as a snake. Once you recognize that it‚Äôs a rope, the illusory snake dissipates; the YogƒÅcƒÅra philosophers go further, to suggest that once you recognize that all you are tracking is patterns of contrast, shading, texture, and the like, the rope will dissipate as well. I tend to agree with them, and I tend to think it‚Äôs possible to experience all of the persisting and stable phenomena that we encounter as illusory. But if you go this way, there are likely to be many kinds of *experienced* phenomena that you can‚Äôt really get rid of. In each sensory domain, and in the domain of thinking, there will be momentary experiences that can be identified in terms of simple and relatively determinate properties (e.g., change in pressure, change in temperature, flows of breath through the body, edges, orientations, blurring, variations in shade, wanting, liking, fearing, etc). I don‚Äôt know exactly what is going to be left over when you pull apart the apparently stable and persisting objects (which you need to do if you are going anti-essentialist). But what I‚Äôm wondering about is this: why not eliminate the complex qualia that show up in everyday experience, and then look for identities in the domain of momentary experiences that are constantly rising, falling, and changing. \n\nThis is a long comment, and probably still not clear enough as we are coming at things from different perspectives. But hopefully it‚Äôs enough to generate a discussion...",
